Migrated to the filestream cmod (deterministic, one input line per thread cycle).
This FIXED the streaming-timing xfail: all 100 real-input sample rows now match the
classic expected byte-for-byte (the 18 type-converting mux_generic outputs and the
mux-gen.16 debounce are all correct).

The only remaining difference is the 5 trailing held-last rows (samples 101-105).
The classic streamer FIFO (depth=100) could hold depth-1=99 entries, so when the
test preloaded 100 input lines the 100th (`1 4`, the one line where sel flips to 1)
overflowed and was DROPPED — the classic then held the 99th (sel=0) for the tail.
filestream loads all 100 input lines (no overflow drop), so it correctly holds the
100th (sel=1) for the tail. Sibling tests/multiclick (also 100 lines) matches
exactly because its 100th line equals its 99th, making the classic's drop invisible.

So this is a benign classic-FIFO-overflow artifact in the golden file, not a
filestream defect. Resolve by either regenerating expected from the deterministic
filestream output, or having filestream replicate the classic drop-on-overflow.
